## Day 2: Creating My First Local Git Repo ( On Mac )

ğŸ“˜ What I Learned:
- A Git repository is just a folder Git watches for changes.
- `git init` tells Git to start tracking that folder.
- `touch` creates a new empty file.
- `echo "text" >> file` adds text into a file.

ğŸ’» Commands Used:

cd ~
mkdir git-practice
cd git-practice
git init
touch README.md
echo "# My First Git Repo" >> README.md
git status


ğŸ§  Day 2 Git Commands with Explanations

ğŸ”¹ mkdir folder-name
ğŸ“Œ Use: Creates a new folder (also called a directory).
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: To organize your projects. You usually make a new folder for each Git repo.
ğŸ’» Example: mkdir git-practice

ğŸ”¹ cd folder-name
ğŸ“Œ Use: Moves into the folder you just created.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: Git commands only work inside a Git repository.
ğŸ’» Example: cd git-practice

ğŸ”¹ git init
ğŸ“Œ Use: Initializes an empty Git repository in the current folder.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: Tells Git to start tracking changes in this folder.
ğŸ“ Creates a hidden .git folder where Git stores all version history.
ğŸ”„ Use once per project.

ğŸ”¹ touch filename
ğŸ“Œ Use: Creates a new empty file.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: Helps you start tracking a file like README.md or main.py.
ğŸ’» Example: touch README.md

ğŸ”¹ echo "some text" >> filename
ğŸ“Œ Use: Adds text to a file from the terminal.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: Quickly creates or edits file contents without opening an editor.
ğŸ’¡ Double >> appends to the file (wonâ€™t erase previous content).

ğŸ”¹ ls -a
ğŸ“Œ Use: Lists all files, including hidden ones like .git.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: Helps you check if your folder is a Git repo (look for .git).
ğŸ’» Output: .git README.md

ğŸ”¹ git status
ğŸ“Œ Use: Shows the current state of your working directory and Git repo.
ğŸ› ï¸ Why: It tells you:
Which files are untracked
Which files have been modified
Which files are staged (ready to be committed)
ğŸ§ª You'll use this command frequently to check what Git sees.

